{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0870e89a-1d52-4689-aa73-1a5702a8a809","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Expensive Glob Pattern (`**\\*.*`)\n**Line 9 in EvalHeavy.csproj** — The `AdditionalFiles` item uses a recursive wildcard `**\\*.*` which forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. This is one of the costliest evaluation operations, especially as the project grows.\n\n## 2. File I/O via Property Function\n**Line 13** — `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` performs disk I/O during evaluation. Property functions that read files block evaluation and bypass MSBuild's caching/up-to-date tracking. This should be a build target or a content item instead.\n\n## 3. Deeply Chained Imports\n**`imports/level1.props → level2.props → level3.props`** — Three levels of transitive imports. Each import adds evaluation overhead (file open, parse, merge). While 3 levels is moderate, this pattern tends to grow over time and compounds with the other issues.\n\n## Recommendations\n| Issue | Fix |\n|-------|-----|\n| Recursive glob | Narrow the glob (e.g., `*.cs`) or move to a target with incremental inputs |\n| `ReadAllText` in property | Move to a target using `ReadLinesFromFile` or make it a `Content` item |\n| Nested imports | Flatten into a single `.props` file or use `Directory.Build.props` |\n\nThe recursive glob and the `ReadAllText` call are the most impactful — both perform I/O on every evaluation pass (design-time builds in IDEs trigger evaluation frequently).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ed5e8630-a7e3-480a-b624-99289117b5c9","outputTokens":400,"requestId":"1C31:348511:78AC83C:852B0E3:69F40143"},"id":"a1f8ef30-b35a-4aa6-93dc-79173a778f57","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:26:38.409Z","parentId":"9f506b25-494f-40ad-92d0-59dfab4e94be"}
